Brookies (makes 20)
A brownie base topped with cookie dough, baked together.
Brownie Layer
	∙	8 oz (225g) high-quality dark chocolate (70%), roughly chopped (Valrhona or Guittard if you can)
	∙	¾ cup (1½ sticks) unsalted butter
	∙	1 cup granulated sugar
	∙	½ cup dark brown sugar, packed
	∙	3 large eggs + 1 yolk, room temperature
	∙	2 tsp vanilla extract
	∙	1 tsp espresso powder (doesn’t make it taste like coffee — just amplifies chocolate)
	∙	¾ cup all-purpose flour
	∙	½ cup Dutch-process cocoa powder
	∙	½ tsp fine sea salt
Cookie Dough Layer
	∙	¾ cup (1½ sticks) unsalted butter, browned and cooled
	∙	¾ cup dark brown sugar, packed
	∙	¼ cup granulated sugar
	∙	1 large egg + 1 yolk
	∙	2 tsp vanilla extract
	∙	2 cups all-purpose flour
	∙	1 tsp cornstarch
	∙	1 tsp baking soda
	∙	1 tsp fine sea salt
	∙	1 cup semi-sweet chocolate chips/chunks
	∙	Flaky sea salt for finishing
Instructions
Cookie dough (make first):
	1.	Brown the butter. Melt butter in a saucepan over medium heat until amber and nutty. Pour into a bowl, cool to room temp.
	2.	Mix wet. Whisk browned butter with both sugars until smooth. Add egg, yolk, and vanilla, whisk until glossy.
	3.	Combine dry. Whisk flour, cornstarch, baking soda, and salt separately.
	4.	Fold together. Add dry to wet, mix until just combined. Fold in chocolate chips. Refrigerate while you make the brownie layer.
Brownie layer:
	5.	Melt chocolate and butter. Set up a double boiler or microwave in 30-second bursts, stirring between. Combine chopped chocolate and butter until completely smooth. Cool slightly.
	6.	Mix sugars and eggs. In a large bowl, whisk both sugars with eggs, yolk, vanilla, and espresso powder until thick and slightly ribbony — about 2 minutes by hand. This is what gives you that crackly, shiny top.
	7.	Combine. Pour the chocolate-butter mixture into the egg mixture, fold until smooth. Sift in flour, cocoa, and salt. Fold gently until just combined — do not overmix or you lose the fudgy texture.
Assemble & bake:
	8.	Prep pan. Preheat oven to 350°F (180°C). Line a 9x13 pan with parchment, leaving overhang for easy removal. Lightly grease.
	9.	Layer. Pour brownie batter into the pan, spread evenly. Take the chilled cookie dough and flatten pieces in your hands, then lay them across the top like a patchwork — it doesn’t need to be perfect. Some brownie should peek through.
	10.	Bake. 28–35 minutes. The cookie layer should be golden and set, and a toothpick in the brownie layer should come out with moist crumbs (not wet batter, not clean). Pull it early rather than late — carryover heat finishes the job.
	11.	Finish. Immediately sprinkle with flaky sea salt. Cool completely in the pan (at least 1–2 hours, ideally 3). The brownie layer needs time to set or it’ll be a gooey mess when you cut.
	12.	Cut. Use the parchment overhang to lift out, then cut into 20 bars with a sharp knife wiped clean between cuts.
